english:
  title: Epitaph and Preface for Lord Ha of Jinyang, Minister of State of the Great Ming Joseon, Posthumously Honored with Titles of Merit
  author: Byeon Gyeyangm
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the eleventh year of Yongle, in the winter month of the year Imjin, the Left Minister of State Jinsan Hojong addressed me, saying: "Our late father planted virtue without tasting its fruits himself, bequeathing all blessing to his descendants. Thus my unworthy self has twice drunk the covenant wine of merit-makers, and now stands foremost among all officials. Moreover, I have received imperial grace and threefold elevation of honors upon my house. For this tomb-way, we wish to raise a monument to show to coming generations the resting place of our ancestors, that none may err in remembrance. Surely such a work requires words, yet I have not composed them. Will you not take up the brush?"

    I dared not refuse. Let me respectfully record: The Lord bore the surname Ha, with personal name Yunryun and courtesy name Sokaae. He came from the great families of Jinyang. Among his ancestors was a Left Minister of State surnamed Ha, named Gongjin, who served with distinction in the court of King Hyeonjong of Goryeo and was posthumously appointed Attendant Counselor and Grand Secretariat Concurrently.

    His great-grandfather, named Busim, achieved the highest examinations but chose to live in retirement. His grandfather, named Sik, received posthumous titles of Pure Loyalty and Merit, serving as Judge of the Ministry of Justice and Lord of Jinwon. His father, named Siyuan, likewise received high posthumous honors including Minister of the Right and Lord of Jingang.

    The Lord was born in the fourth month of the year Sinyou under the Yuan Dynasty to a mother of the Jeong clan. At seven years old, when his mother passed into the realm beyond, he wept with grief as though a grown man. At fourteen he began his studies. A noted elder of the district, recognizing virtue in his line, gave him his daughter in marriage, saying: "Those whose ancestors served the nation with merit shall surely see their descendants flourish."

    The Lord entered service under King Chungmok as Recorder of Ceremonial Affairs. In time, through diligent service, he advanced through many offices. As the end of Goryeo drew near and the royal treasury emptied, the Lord, though burdened with the provision of daily needs for the court, performed his duties without complaint, earning the praise of all officials.

    When a foreign threat arose from the south and west, the Lord served as magistrate of Sukju, managing the passage of armies with such grace and provision that soldiers spoke of his kindness. When famine struck, he reduced his own stipend to aid the hungry, convincing the wealthy to share their stores. Through his governance, harsh taxes ceased and punishments grew few, so that both officers and common folk blessed his memory.

    Upon his retirement to the countryside, the Lord foresaw danger from island raiders and counseled his kinsmen to move northward to higher ground. When the raiders came, his foresight saved his entire household while others suffered loss. His son, now risen to the highest rank, sought to honor his aging father by securing him an administrative post in a safer region, that he might live in peace.

    In his sixtieth year, having seen his son established in great office and his household secure, the Lord spoke to his wife: "I have no regrets. Human life is brief or long as Heaven decrees, and all must reach their end. There is only the matter of sequence." He then peacefully departed this life.

    His son bore him with great ceremony to their ancestral lands in Jinyang and interred him with rites according to the Family Ritual of Master Zhu, using no Buddhist practices. The court subsequently honored him with titles of the highest merit, and his lady wife received noble rank.

    The Lord was of thick substance and grave deportment, clean in his conduct and spare in his speech. He harbored no idle gossip nor jest. He never concerned himself with accumulating property. His filial piety and brotherly affection arose from his nature. He brought harmony to his clan and peace to his village, dwelling always in contentment.

    When his father's elder brother refused to divide the inheritance fairly, his younger brother wished to petition the magistrate. But the Lord said: "How could I dare contend with my uncle?" and stopped the suit. After the uncle's death, when the matter was pressed again, he refused once more, saying: "Let not brothers contend in court." When the Lord himself had passed, the suit proceeded and the estate was divided, yet his son refused his portion, saying: "This is not what our father would have done. How could I accept it?" Even when offered a portion for his own sons, he declined, saying: "If my sons receive it, then I receive it," and would not permit it.

    His lady wife, the Jeong clan woman, was skilled in household management and devoted to propriety. She honored her parents with filial grace and served her husband with perfect harmony. She taught her children with both rigor and mercy, and showed kindness and completeness toward all relations. In her declining years, though her son urged her to take medicine and prolong her life, she refused, saying: "My husband has long departed. That I have lived to see your glory brings me contentment. I have no wish to cling to life further." She passed peacefully the next day at the age of seventy-six.

    The Lord left issue: one son of distinguished bearing who rose to the highest offices of the realm, several daughters married to men of rank, and descendants of great promise. The blessings that flowed from his virtue extended far into the generations that followed.

    Reflecting upon this, I see in the Lord and his line the truth of the ancient saying: "Good deeds receive their reward." From this day until ten thousand ages hence, the grace he planted shall endure without end.

    Hark! The inscription reads:

    The flowing stream has its deep source,
    The spreading branch its sturdy root.
    Glorious was the Ha family line,
    A house of virtue and of worth.
    Their ancestor, left minister of rank,
    Won honor through his service true,
    Accumulating goodness deep,
    He opened blessings for his blood.

    Diligent in nurturing virtue's way,
    Lord Ha of Jinyang held his course.
    He mended kinship's broken bonds,
    And men revered his righteousness.
    Foreseeing danger, he removed his house,
    And wisdom saved him from the sword.
    His mercy graced two districts fair,
    Where people clung to him as kin.

    With wisdom joined to righteousness,
    He should have claimed his place on high,
    Yet choosing stillness in his years,
    He never raised his hand again.
    Heaven blessed his goodness vast,
    And gave him sons of brilliant mind.
    They met the sage who rules our realm,
    And brought him counsel strong and true.

    In halls and courts they sat with grace,
    And brought a hundred things to life.
    Their weight like great Mount Tai itself,
    Their measure like the boundless sea.
    They stand as summit of all merit,
    As scholars' foremost sage and guide.
    The throne has raised them to the sky,
    And honored three generations deep.

    Their mother too received high rank,
    Posthumously exalted high.
    The virtue hidden now shows forth—
    Though dead, they live eternally.
    Jinyang stands tall with Jinyang waters clear,
    Above their graves the auspicious gathers near.
    Both father and mother rest in sacred ground,
    Where blessings flow forever without bound.

    Graved upon this stone it stands,
    To echo through the endless years.
    Whose eyes fall on these words will know
    The merit of the Ha and their great deeds.
